[[File:Lighting system 10,134.jpg|thumb|Electro-Dynamic lighting system patent]]
The ''' Electro-Dynamic Light Company ''' of New York was a lighting and electrical distribution company organized in 1878. The company held the patents for the first practical system of incandescent electric lighting. It was the first company formally established to provided electric lightning and was the first company organized specifically to manufacture and sell [[Incandescent light bulb|incandescent electric light bulbs]]. 

== History ==

[[Albon Man]], a New York attorney, and [[William E. Sawyer]], an electrical engineer, officially formed the Electro-Dynamic Light Company of New York on July 8, 1878.<ref name=officially>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Sawyer's Electric Lamp |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5075079// |newspaper=Fort Wayne Weekly Sentinel  |location=Fort Wayne, Indiana |date=November 13, 1878 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}}}}</ref>{{sfn|EE1890|1890|p=72}}{{sfn|Pope|1894|p=10}} 
This was by way of a partnership with Man supplying money for experiments.<ref name=investors>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Sawyer's New Incandescent Light for Illumination of Buildings |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5074527// |newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune |page=7 |location=Chicago, Illinois |date=April 5, 1880 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> Sources in the late 19th century claimed it to be the first formally established electric-lighting company.{{sfn|Carnegie|2004|p=196}}{{sfn|Wrege|1986|p=59}} 

The Electro-Dynamic Light Company was the first organized specifically to manufacture and sell incandescent electric light bulbs. Man and Sawyer patented the first practical system of incandescent electric lighting and gave the patents to the company. The United States Electric Lighting Company was organized in 1878, weeks after the Electro-Dynamic Company.{{sfn|EE1890|1890|p=72}}{{sfn|WE1890|1890|p=36}}{{sfn|ER1890|1890|p=9}}

The names of other investor-partners of the company besides Man and Sawyer were: [[Hugh McCulloch]] (Man's uncle), William Hercules Hays, [[James Powell Kernochan|James P. Kernochan]], Lawrence Myers, and Jacob Hays.{{sfn|Pope|1894|p=10}}<ref name=1878lamp>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Another Electric Lamp |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5042574// |newspaper=Democrat and Chronicle |location=Rochester, New York |date=November 1, 1878 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> Sawyer was about 28 years old and Man about 52 years old at the time the company was formed. They planned on lighting New York City with electricity for one-fortieth the cost of gas lighting.<ref name=fortieth>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Another Electric Light / An Inventor who Proposes Household Illumination at One-Fortieth the Cost of Gas |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5073776// |newspaper=The Belvidere Standard |page=7 |location=Belvidere, Illinois |date=November 12, 1878 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref><ref name=Tenn> {{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=An Inventor Who Promises Illumination at One-Fortieth Cost of Gas |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5120257// |newspaper= The Tennessean|location=Nashville, Tennessee |date=November 3, 1878 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }} </ref> The new company started with capital of $10,000 cash and $290,000 of scrip.{{sfn|Pope|1894|p=10}} It was formed for the purpose of the production of light and power by means of electricity for the lighting of streets and buildings. The company was to make all the equipment necessary to generate and distribute electricity.<ref name=AllEquip>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=The Electric Lamp / An Invention which finds an Important Manufacturing Center in Brooklyn – The Company which is Prepared to Carry the Work to Consumption  |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5073894// |newspaper=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle |page=5 |location=Brooklyn, New York |date= October 14, 1883 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> The distribution of electricity produced by the company was not only for lighting, but for other purposes as well.{{sfn|NAR1889|1889|p=654}}
[[File:Sawyer electric lamp 205144.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Electric lamp patented 1878]]
In 1878, the Electro-Dynamic Light Company demonstrated an electric light that was the invention of Sawyer and Man. An exhibition was set up in New York City on October 29, 1878.<ref name=ChicagoTrib> {{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=The Electro-Dynamic Light Company ready to Commence Operation  |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5121139// |newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune |location=Chicago, Illinois |date=November 1, 1878 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }} </ref> The same exhibition was mentioned several weeks later in a newspaper of Princeton, Minnesota,<ref name=yesterday> {{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=A New Electric Light |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5119971// |newspaper= The Princeton Union|location=Princeton, Minnesota |date=November 13, 1878 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }} </ref> and Bismarck, North Dakota.<ref name=Bismarck> {{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=A New Electric Light |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5120096// |newspaper=Bismarck |location=Bismarck, North Dakota |date=November 18, 1878 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }} </ref> The lamp was described as a strip of pencil [[graphite|carbon graphite]] connected with two wires to an electric generator. The carbon strip was in a [[hermetically sealed]] glass bulb that was filled with [[nitrogen]] gas. When electricity was applied, the internal strip developed a temperature of between 30,000 and 50,000 degrees [[Fahrenheit]]. Since there was no oxygen in the glass globe the carbon filament did not burn out and produced light instead.<ref name=Electro-Dynami>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= A New Electric Light / The Electro-Dynamic Light Company / Ready to Commence Operations |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5045915// |newspaper=The New York Times |location=New York City |date= October 30, 1878 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref>

The demonstration consisted of five electric light bulbs hanging from [[chandelier]]s in an office building at the corner of Elm and Walker Streets. Wires came from the electric lights and went to an adjacent room where there was a generator set up to produce electricity. The wires passed through keyholes to the adjoining room. A key was put into the keyhole and turned to switch on the electric current. As the key was turned further around, the electric lights got brighter. This switch idea was demonstrated with all five chandeliers with the electric lamps. An electric meter to measure the amount of electricity used in an office or house for billing purposes was also demonstrated.<ref name=1878lamp/>

[[Thomas Edison]]'s electric lighting discoveries were first shown in September 1878. The Edison Electric-Light Company of New York was organized on October 17, three months after the Electro-Dynamic Company was formally established.{{sfn|NAR1889|1889|p=654}} The United States Electric-Lighting Company of New York was formed shortly after this to introduce the inventions of [[Hiram S. Maxim]] and [[Edward Weston]].{{sfn|NAR1889|1889|p=654}}

== Legal ==

Patents were taken out by Man and Sawyer for all the items needed for electric current distribution.<ref name=1878lamp/> The patents were for the benefit of the Electro-Dynamic Light Company of New York.<ref name=Electro-Dynami/> Man and Sawyer were involved in many legal actions between 1880 and 1884 to protect these patents for electric lighting.<ref name=legalfirst>{{Citation |last=Shaver |first=Lea |year= 2012 |title=Illuminating Innovation: From Patent Racing to Patent War |publisher=The Washington and Lee Law Review (Vol. 69, No. 4)|publication-place=Lexington, Virginia |page= 1917|url= |accessdate= }}</ref>{{sfn|World_XLV|1905|p=414}}<ref name=TheCourts>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= An Injuction against United States Electric Light Company asked for|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5075161// |newspaper=National Republican |page=3 |location=Washington, D.C. |date=November 11, 1883 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref>

== Demise ==

The Electro-Dynamic Light Company ceased to exist after 1881.<ref name=Thesis>
{{cite journal |url=http://www.thebhc.org/sites/default/files/beh/BEHprint/v013/p0031-p0049.pdf |title=William E. Sawyer and the Rise and Fall of America's First Incandescent Electric Light Company, 1878–1881 |last1=Wrege |first1=Charles D. |last2=Greenwood |first2=Ronald G. |author-link=Charles D. Wrege|journal=Business and Economic History |series=2d |volume=13 |date=1984 |pages=31–48 |publisher=The Business History Conference |access-date=15 May 2017|format=PDF}}</ref>

