{{redirect|MEO}} {{Comparison satellite navigation orbits}} [[File:Orbitalaltitudes.jpg|thumb|To-scale diagram of low, medium, and [[high Earth orbit]]s]]
'''Medium Earth orbit''' ('''MEO'''), sometimes called '''intermediate circular orbit''' ('''ICO'''), is the region of [[outer space|space]] around [[Earth]] above [[low Earth orbit]] ([[altitude]] of {{convert|2000|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} above [[sea level]]) and below [[geostationary orbit]] (altitude of {{convert|35786|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} above sea level).<ref name=nasa20120718> {{cite web |title=Definitions of geocentric orbits from the Goddard Space Flight Center |url=http://gcmd.nasa.gov/User/suppguide/platforms/orbit.html |work=User support guide: platforms |publisher=NASA Goddard Space Flight Center |accessdate=2012-07-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527132541/http://gcmd.nasa.gov/User/suppguide/platforms/orbit.html |archivedate=May 27, 2010 }}</ref>
The most common use for [[satellite]]s in this region is for [[navigation]], [[communication]], and [[geodesy|geodetic]]/[[space environment]] science.<ref name=nasa20120718/> The most common altitude is approximately {{convert|20200|km|mi|0}}), which yields an [[orbital period]] of 12 hours, as used, for example, by the [[Global Positioning System]] (GPS).<ref name=nasa20120718/> Other satellites in medium Earth orbit include [[GLONASS|Glonass]] (with an altitude of {{convert|19100|km|mi|0}}){{citation needed|date=July 2012}} and [[Galileo positioning system|Galileo]] (with an altitude of {{convert|23222|km|mi|0}})<ref>[http://www.esa.int/Our_Activities/Navigation/Galileo/Galileo_satellites Galileo Satellites]</ref> constellations. Communications satellites that cover the North and South Pole are also put in MEO.<ref>[http://exnetapps.intelsat.com/resources/satellite-basics/benefits.asp Satellite Basics: Solution Benefits<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20131119183307/http://exnetapps.intelsat.com/resources/satellite-basics/benefits.asp |date=2013-11-19 }}</ref>
The [[orbital period]]s of MEO satellites range from about 2 to nearly 24 hours.<ref name=nasa20120718/> [[Telstar]] 1, an experimental satellite launched in 1962, orbited in MEO.<ref>[http://iml.jou.ufl.edu/projects/Fall99/Coffey/MEO.HTM Medium Earth Orbit<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
The orbit is home to a number of [[satellite|artificial satellites]].<ref name=nasa20120718/>
